    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1976-11-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1976-11-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="167"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                <head>167. National Security Study Memorandum 248<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d167fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_FGR1">Ford</persName>
                        Library, National Security Adviser, <persName corresp="#p_SB3">Brent
                            Scowcroft</persName> Daily Work Files, Box 70, Chronological File B.
                        Secret. <persName corresp="#p_HWG1">Hyland</persName> signed the memorandum
                        for <persName corresp="#p_SB3">Scowcroft</persName>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d167fn2">Assistant to the President for
                        National Security Affairs <persName corresp="#p_SB3">Scowcroft</persName>
                        tasked the Departments of State and Defense and the <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                            >CIA</gloss> with conducting a brief study of U.S. policy options, and
                        underlying assumptions, regarding future relations with Ethiopia.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1976-11-13"
                        >November 13, 1976</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO:</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                    <item>The Chairman, Joint Chiefs of Staff</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>United States Goals in Relation to Ethiopia</item>
                </list>
                <p>In the light of the dramatic changes which have occurred in Ethiopia since
                    Emperor <persName corresp="#p_HSI1">Haile Selassie</persName> was deposed in
                    September 1974, the President has directed a brief study of United States policy
                    options, and the underlying assumptions, regarding the state of our future
                    relations with Ethiopia.</p>
                <p>The study should draw as appropriate on the studies under <gloss
                        target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss>s 239 and 184, and take account of more recent
                    assessments of the situation. The study should: <list>
                        <item>—Review current and possible future United States interests,
                            objectives and policy in the Horn of Africa and the Red Sea area,
                            including military and economic assistance programs.</item>
                        <item>—Assess the internal security and stability of Ethiopia and its
                            present government.</item>
                        <item>—Assess current Ethiopian policy toward the United States, the Soviet
                            Union, the People’s Republic of China and Ethiopia’s African and Arab
                            neighbors.</item>
                        <item>—Assess the internal problems Ethiopia faces and the role Ethiopia
                            might play in the Horn of Africa, and the larger African scene, over the
                            next year.</item>
                        <pb facs="d167-02" n="2" xml:id="d167-02"/>
                        <item>—Assess Soviet policy toward Ethiopia, Somalia and the FTAI.</item>
                        <item>—Assess the significance of Ethiopia to United States political,
                            economic and military policy in the Horn of Africa and the Red Sea
                            area.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The study should determine United States goals with regard to Ethiopia and policy
                    options for achieving these goals. The study should be prepared by the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for Africa and should
                    be completed by December 10.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWG1">William G. Hyland</persName> for <lb/>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SB3">Brent Scowcroft</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
